{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2017}} {{infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] --> | name = Parry Aftab | image = ParryAftab 01.jpg | caption = Aftab in 2016 | imagesize = | alt = | pseudonym = | birth_name = | birth_date = <!-- uncomment the template to use it: {{Birth date and age|year|mo|da}} --> | birth_place = | death_date = | death_place = | resting_place = | occupation = Lawyer, author, charity head, board member, speaker, consultant | language = English, Spanish and some Russian | nationality = US | ethnicity = | citizenship = US | education = Juris Doctorate, NYU School of Law 1984, Hunter College B.S. Economics/Thomas Hunter Honors Program, Phi Beta Kappa Nu Chapter | alma_mater = | period = | genre = | subject = | movement = | notableworks = The Parent's Guide to the Internet, StopCyberbullying Global, A Parents Guide to Protecting Your Children in Cyberspace | spouse(s) = | partner(s) = | children = | relative(s) = | influences = | influenced = | awards = FBI Director's Award, White House Presidents Service Award (accepted for her organization), Royal Canadian Mounted Police Child Recovery Award, Media Ecology Award, Family PC Magazine Internet Visionary Award | signature = | signature_alt = | website = {{URL|http://aftab.com/}} }}
'''Parry Aftab''' is an Internet privacy and security lawyer, considered one of the founders of cyberlaw and founder of the world's largest and oldest cybersafety charity. Named by The Boston Herald as "the leading expert in cybercrime in the world," Ms. Aftab wrote the first cybersafety book in the world for parents (in 1996) and has received a long list of honors and has been appointed to the boards of directors and advisory boards of several companies, including TRUSTe, Facebook, MTV and Sesame Street Online.<ref>[https://www.bloomberg.com/research/stocks/people/person.asp?personId=12035893&capId=108192338&previousCapId=108192338&previousTitle=WiredTrust]</ref> She is a longtime Internet safety expert<ref name="TheTruthAboutTeensSexting"/> who founded the Internet safety organization WiredSafety, StopCyberbullying and the consulting firm, WiredTrust. She was "the Privacy Lawyer" columnist for Information Week Magazine for many years. In 2016 Parry Aftab founded Cybersafety India and the StopCyberbullying and sextortion and morphing prevention initiatives for India. <ref>[http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/bengaluru/Pioneers-of-USs-anti-cyber-bullying-movement-to-launch-India-campaign/articleshow/52528964.cms]</ref> She resides in both the US and Canada.
==Career== Aftab was appointed by UNESCO's Director General Federico Mayor as the chief of the U.S. National Action Committee for [[UNESCO]]'s World Citizen's Committee on Protecting Innocence in Danger group in 1999 to address online sexual exploitation of children.<ref>[http://www.cnn.com/WORLD/americas/9906/15/un.pedophilia/ UNESCO launches campaign to fight Internet pedophilia]. CNN (June 15, 1999). Retrieved on December 28, 2015.</ref> She became a member of the Board of Directors for the non-profit, [[TRUSTe]] in 2003.<ref>[https://www.clickz.com/clickz/news/1715430/execs-accounts-february-14-2003# Execs and Accounts for February 14, 2003]. ClickZ (February 14, 2003). Retrieved on December 28, 2015.</ref> In 2005, the [[United States Congress]] issued a [[non-binding resolution|resolution]] that recognized her efforts to combat [[cyberbullying]] as Executive Director of StopCyberbullying and WiredSafety.<ref>{{cite book|title=Congressional Record, Volume 151, Part 8, May 19, 2005 to June 6, 2005 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vWBxXUEZ13EC&pg=PA870 |publisher=Government Printing Office |pages=870–}}</ref>
Her organization, WiredSafety, became a member of Facebook's Safety Advisory Board in 2009<ref name="Find Law">{{cite news|last1=El-Rahman|first1=Minara|title=Facebook Safety|url=https://blogs.findlaw.com/law_and_life/2009/12/facebook-safety-board-works-on-kids-and-safety-policy.html|accessdate=Dec 16, 2015|publisher=Find Law}}{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> and in April, Aftab appeared on [[Good Morning America]] for its [[town hall meeting]] on sexting.<ref name="TheTruthAboutTeensSexting">{{cite web | last = Kazdin | first = Cole and Imaeyen Ibanga | title = The Truth About Teens Sexting; 'GMA' Holds a Town Hall Meeting to Discuss the Growing Teen Trend | url = http://abcnews.go.com/GMA/story?id=7337547 | work = [[Good Morning America]] | publisher = [[American Broadcasting Company|WABC]] | date = April 15, 2009 | accessdate = May 31, 2010}} </ref> In 2010 she received the FBI Director's Community Leadership Award and<ref name="FBIAward">{{cite web | last = Travers | first = Bryan L. | title = Child Safety Advocate and Cyber Law Legal Expert to Be Honored by FBI Director | url = http://newark.fbi.gov/pressrel/pressrel10/nk112210.htm | publisher = [[Federal Bureau of Investigation|FBI]] Press Release | date = November 22, 2010 | accessdate = November 26, 2010}} </ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://cliffviewpilot.com/childrens-cyber-protector-parry-aftab-of-bergen-honored-by-fbi/|title=Children’s cyber protector Parry Aftab of Bergen honored by FBI|work=Cliffview Pilot|accessdate=December 23, 2015}}</ref> was one of 28 members in the Online Safety and Technology Working Group of the [[National Telecommunications and Information Administration]].<ref>(June 4, 2010) [https://www.ntia.doc.gov/legacy/reports/2010/OSTWG_Final_Report_060410.pdf OSTWG Final Report], accessed December 22, 2015</ref> She was one of 29 members of the Internet Safety Technical Task Force, run by Harvard's Berkman Center.<ref>[https://cyber.harvard